:name: Hisense W41H1 RS-485 driver QA (Renode)
:description: Run the RS-485 driver on an emulated RTL8710C core, UART0 bridged
:description: to the Python virtual A/C -- Layer-3 QA with no physical chip.

# Usage:
#   renode firmware/test/renode/hisense_qa.resc
# then in another shell wire the virtual A/C to UART0's socket (see README).

using sysbus
mach create "w41h1"
machine LoadPlatformDescription @firmware/test/renode/rtl8710c.repl

# --- firmware to run ---
# Prefer a SMALL bare-metal driver-test ELF (renode/README.md explains why the
# full Matter image is a poor first target). Point $bin at your ELF:
$bin ?= @firmware/test/renode/driver_test.elf
# For a raw .bin instead of an ELF, load at the RAM/XIP base and set PC/SP.
# sysbus LoadBinary $bin 0x10000000

macro reset
"""
    sysbus LoadELF $bin
"""
runMacro $reset

# --- expose UART0 as a TCP socket so the virtual A/C can attach ---
# Renode side: TCP server on :3456 carrying UART0 bytes.
emulation CreateServerSocketTerminal 3456 "acbus"
connector Connect uart0 acbus

# Watch what the driver transmits (optional):
# uart0 CreateFileBackedTerminal @/tmp/uart0.log

showAnalyzer uart0
echo ""
echo ">>> UART0 is on TCP :3456. In another shell bridge it to the virtual A/C:"
echo ">>>   socat -d -d TCP:127.0.0.1:3456 PTY,raw,link=/tmp/acpty &"
echo ">>>   python3 firmware/test/virtual_ac.py --port /tmp/acpty"
echo ">>> Then:  start"
